│ (MemCheckExp.isInsertedInstruction(&I))\n      continue;\n                  │
│ SE.forgetValue(&I);\n    I.eraseFromParent();\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe code      │
│ assumes that if `MemRuntimeCheckCond` is non-null, then `MemCheckBlock` is  │
│ also non-null and can be safely dereferenced. However, in this reproducer   │
│ case, `MemRuntimeCheckCond` appears to be set but `MemCheckBlock` is null   │
│ (as observed in the debugger where `MemCheckBlock` was `0x0`).\n\nThis      │
│ creates a situation where the code tries to iterate over `*MemCheckBlock`   │
│ when `MemCheckBlock` is null, leading to undefined behavior. Even if it     │
│ doesn't crash immediately, it can leave the SCEV expander in an             │
│ inconsistent state where instructions are marked as inserted but their      │
│ users are not properly tracked.\n\nThe root cause is that the condition     │
│ should check both `MemRuntimeCheckCond` AND `MemCheckBlock` before          │
│ attempting to iterate over the block's instructions.\n\n4. Proposed Edit    │
│ Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to add a null check for `MemCheckBlock` in the      │
│ memory runtime check cleanup code. The condition should be:\n\n```cpp\nif   │
│ (MemRuntimeCheckCond && MemCheckBlock)\n```\n\nThis ensures that we only    │
│ attempt to clean up the memory check block if both the condition and the    │
│ block exist.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nThe fix adds a proper null check to       │
│ prevent the cleanup code from dereferencing a null `MemCheckBlock` pointer. │
│ This ensures that the SCEV expander cleaner maintains its invariant that    │
│ removed instructions are only used by other inserted instructions,          │
│ preventing the assertion failure. The fix is minimal and targeted,          │
│ addressing the exact root cause without affecting other functionality."})   │
