│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                             │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ The assertion failure occurs in `SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup()` because an │
│ instruction that was inserted during SCEV expansion has users that are not  │
│ part of the inserted instruction set. This violates the assumption that     │
│ during cleanup, any instruction being removed should only be used by other  │
│ instructions that were also inserted during the same expansion process.     │
│                                                                             │
│ From the debugger analysis, we found that:                                  │
│ - The failing instruction is an `add` instruction (opcode 13) with operands │
│ `%N` and constant `1`                                                       │
│ - This instruction is in the `entry` block                                  │
│ - It has a user that is an `icmp` instruction (opcode 56) also in the       │
│ `entry` block                                                               │
│ - The `MemCheckBlock` is null, indicating no memory runtime checks were     │
│ generated                                                                   │
│ - The `MemRuntimeCheckCond` is null                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ The scalar evolution analysis shows that the loop has a backedge-taken      │
│ count of `(99 + (-1 * %N) + ((1 + %N) smax (-99 + %N)))` with a constant    │
│ max of 100. The key observation is that the loop contains complex exit      │
│ conditions that involve `%N` in arithmetic operations.                      │
│                                                                             │
│ The issue arises during the cleanup phase of `GeneratedRTChecks`. The       │
│ `GeneratedRTChecks` destructor attempts to clean up both SCEV and memory    │
│ check expanders, but the memory check cleanup code assumes that if          │
│ `MemRuntimeCheckCond` exists, then `MemCheckBlock` also exists and contains │
│ instructions that may reference expanded values.                            │
│                                                                             │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the `GeneratedRTChecks` destructor in `LoopVectorize.cpp` lines  │
│ 2070-2088, the problem is in the memory check cleanup logic:                │
│                                                                             │
│ ```cpp                                                                      │
│ if (MemRuntimeCheckCond) {                                                  │
│   auto &SE = *MemCheckExp.getSE();                                          │
│   // Memory runtime check generation creates compares that use expanded     │
│   // values. Remove them before running the SCEVExpanderCleaners.           │
│   for (auto &I : make_early_inc_range(reverse(*MemCheckBlock))) {           │
│     if (MemCheckExp.isInsertedInstruction(&I))                              │
│       continue;                                                             │
│     SE.forgetValue(&I);                                                     │
│     I.eraseFromParent();                                                    │
│   }                                                                         │
│ }                                                                           │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ The code assumes that if `MemRuntimeCheckCond` is non-null, then            │
│ `MemCheckBlock` is also non-null and can be safely dereferenced. However,   │
│ in this reproducer case, `MemRuntimeCheckCond` appears to be set but        │
│ `MemCheckBlock` is null (as observed in the debugger where `MemCheckBlock`  │
│ was `0x0`).                                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ This creates a situation where the code tries to iterate over               │
│ `*MemCheckBlock` when `MemCheckBlock` is null, leading to undefined         │
│ behavior. Even if it doesn't crash immediately, it can leave the SCEV       │
│ expander in an inconsistent state where instructions are marked as inserted │
│ but their users are not properly tracked.                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ The root cause is that the condition should check both                      │
│ `MemRuntimeCheckCond` AND `MemCheckBlock` before attempting to iterate over │
│ the block's instructions.                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ The fix is to add a null check for `MemCheckBlock` in the memory runtime    │
│ check cleanup code. The condition should be:                                │
│                                                                             │
│ ```cpp                                                                      │
│ if (MemRuntimeCheckCond && MemCheckBlock)                                   │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ This ensures that we only attempt to clean up the memory check block if     │
│ both the condition and the block exist.                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                              │
│                                                                             │
│ The fix adds a proper null check to prevent the cleanup code from           │
│ dereferencing a null `MemCheckBlock` pointer. This ensures that the SCEV    │
│ expander cleaner maintains its invariant that removed instructions are only │
│ used by other inserted instructions, preventing the assertion failure. The  │
│ fix is minimal and targeted, addressing the exact root cause without        │
│ affecting other functionality.                                              │
